So I think I am going to ease up on my tasting menu kick, but to finish a run through Guy Savoy, Robuchon, and to end at Picasso ... what a ride.
The service at Picasso was very friendly and attentive.
My 6 courses were staged very well, and I never felt rushed or neglected.
Perhaps because there were not as many plates in my Picasso experience as at Guy or Robuchon, but the segue from light to heavy, from clean to unctuous, from sweeter to savory and back again was a little more abrupt here ... but still artfully done.
I chose the upper-level wine pairing and was very pleased with the matches, though for nearly $900 I might have thought some heavier hitters would be among my selections.
The pastry was well done ... better than Robuchon, but certainly not better than Guy Savoy.
I will say that of all three venues, this is the one I lingered in longest and had an after-dinner cocktail.
Perhaps it was that I had eaten less courses, perhaps it was the ambiance, but the staff was more than gracious to allow me to stare out the window until the wee hours and contemplate a truly wonderful evening.
For that  am thankful.
For that, for the food, for the service and for a great overall experience, the certainly earned their stars.

